'''''Young Jedi Knights: Shards of Alderaan''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] junior novel written by [[Kevin J. Anderson]] and [[Rebecca Moesta]]. It is the seventh installment in the series ''[[Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights]]'', and it was first published in [[January]] [[1997]] by [[Berkley Boulevard]]. The novel was reprinted in the [[1998]] compilation book ''[[Young Jedi Knights: The Fall of the Diversity Alliance]]''.

==Publisher's summary==
''When the Empire died, they were born&mdash;a new hope for the New Republic. The young twins of Han Solo and Princess Leia have taken their first steps as Jedi Knights, defeating the evil minions of the Shadow Academy. Now, with their friends Tenel Ka and Lowbacca the Wookiee, the future heroes of an already legendary saga continue their training.''

''Jacen and Jaina set off for the Alderaan system, determined to salvage a piece of the shattered planet as a gift for their mother. But amid the ghosts of a dead world, the twins are in for a deadly surprise: some ghosts still live. A long-lost enemy of the Solo family is about to return&hellip;''

==Plot summary==
The [[Jedi Praxeum|Jedi Academy]] rebuilds after the devastating battle against the [[Second Imperium]]. As [[Zekk]] recovers from his injuries, he returns to his home [[Planet/Legends|planet]] of [[Ennth]] to seek new direction. An arrogant noble named [[Raynar Thul]] is a student at the Jedi academy. His [[Parent/Legends|father]] is missing. The [[Diversity Alliance]], an [[Speciesism|anti-human/pro-alien]] extremist group interested in [[Bornan Thul]]'s disappearance, hires [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] to investigate. 

[[Jaina Solo Fel|Jaina]] and [[Darth Caedus|Jacen]], meanwhile, decide to go to the graveyard of [[Alderaan/Legends|Alderaan]], the [[Asteroid field/Legends|asteroid field]] left behind by the planet's destruction. They travel aboard the ''[[Rock Dragon]]'', [[Tenel Ka Djo|Tenel Ka's]] new [[Starship/Legends|ship]] which she received as a gift from her parents. Raynar and [[Lowbacca|Lowie]] are also aboard. The [[Solo twins (disambiguation)|Solo twins]] seek a shard of the planet to give as a gift to their [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|mother]] for her birthday. The ''Rock Dragon'' is attacked by Boba Fett in ''[[Slave IV]]''; he demands the location of Bornan Thul. Zekk comes to the rescue, [[Pilot/Legends|piloting]] the ''[[Lightning Rod]]''. After Fett retreats, Zekk decides to become a [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]], thinking that his [[Force power/Legends|Force abilities]] would be a great advantage.

==Continuity==
{{Quote|Again, there has to be a certain balance to a ret-con for a hardcore fan to buy it, including myself. I think the Ailyn Vel fix had a sufficient confluence of influences ''[''&hellip;'']'' to score higher than average on the believability-meter.|Abel G. Peña|<ref name="Blog" />}}
In [[2005]], the [[Star Wars Insider 80|''Star Wars Insider'' 80]] article "[[The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors|The History of the Mandalorians]]," by [[Abel G. Peña]], revealed that the character [[Ailyn Vel]], daughter of [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]], had been posing as [[Gender/Legends|her]] father, and that Fett himself does not actually appear in ''[[Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights]]''.<ref name="Insider 80">{{InsiderCite|80|The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors}}</ref> Peña gave several reasons for the [[Retroactive continuity|retcon]]: First, he felt that Fett's actions in ''Young Jedi Knights: Shards of Alderaan'' did not match his characterization from previous appearances, most notably the [[1996]] short story "[[The Last One Standing: The Tale of Boba Fett]]." Additionally, in ''[[Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance]]'', the character [[Nolaa Tarkona]] suggests that Fett could be female. These points, coupled with early fan speculation that Fett was female, led Peña to conceive the idea that Fett's previously unnamed child from the [[2001]] [[Star Wars comic books|comic story]] "[[Outbid But Never Outgunned]]" was Vel, a daughter who at times masqueraded as her father.<ref name="Blog">{{Blog|abelgpena|15|The Anatomy of a Retcon 2: or, "Boba Fett? Where?"}}</ref>

